    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, escrow! It's like a trusty little helper in the house-buying world. Imagine you're a wise old wizard, and you've got a magical treasure chest (your house) that you want to give to your apprentice. But you don't want to give it away just yet, so you entrust it to a neutral, trustworthy goblin (the escrow agent) to hold onto until you both agree on the terms. This goblin makes sure that both parties (you and the seller) fulfill their promises before the treasure chest is finally handed over. In the real world, this goblin is called an escrow company, and they hold the money and documents until everything is set right, ensuring that the house is yours and the seller gets their money. It's a way to keep the deal fair and square, without any goblin tricks or sneaky goblin shenanigans!",
      "source": "target",
