      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's essentially how it works. A holdback, also known as a reserve, is a portion of the funds held in escrow that is set aside to cover any repairs, defects, or other issues that are discovered during the home inspection or closing process. The amount set aside as a holdback is typically determined by the terms of the escrow agreement and can vary depending on the specific circumstances of the transaction.\n\nHere's how it works in practice:\n\n1. During the home inspection, the buyer's inspector identifies any issues with the property that need to be addressed. These issues could range from minor cosmetic problems to major structural defects.\n\n2. The buyer and seller negotiate the terms of how these issues will be resolved. This could involve the seller agreeing to make the necessary repairs, the buyer agreeing to pay a certain amount to cover the repairs, or a combination of both.\n\n3. Once an agreement is reached, the seller is given a timeframe to complete the repairs. During this period, the funds set aside as a holdback are held in escrow by the escrow agent.\n\n4. If the seller completes the repairs within the agreed-upon timeframe, the holdback funds are released to the seller, and the rest of the escrow funds are released to the buyer",
